<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-09-07T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-09-07T14:00:00-05:00" n="187" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d187">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/20</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-09-07T19:00:00+00:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">September 7, 1914, 7 p.m.</hi>
                            </date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 10:50 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>621. The agreement between the Allies published to-day that no one will
                            consent to end hostilities till all three consent is England’s
                            declaration to the Kaiser that no peace proposals will be entertained
                            till one side or the other is completely exhausted. The English are
                            preparing for a long war. They mean to fight till promilitarism is
                            utterly crushed.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>